<font color="#FF0000">INNER CIRCLE</font><br>
<tt>Wed Aug 13 17:12:22 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
<br><br>
It was (double posting) like the first time I squeezed the trigger in Nam, by the time the last tracer left the barrel, hell and destruction had taken a life, an NVA's corpsmens life. His sidekick had also been seriously wounded. <br><br>
Found out a lot more of what transpired that I was not aware of also found a publisher, two in fact and they want the book, another wants to turn it into the movie, something about the last war. <br><br>
I met many Marines that we had shared C-rats together now it was $2.99 breakfast at Denny's. I met a corpsmen that should have gotten the Medal of Honor, that was  a site to see. A Marine whom Doc had treated in the field 30 years before. Doc didn't know if the Marine had lived. All he remembered was trying to find the bullet holes in the mud covered Marine. The Marine having been shot three times continued to call in airstrikes, napalm and artillery. Naval gun fire for the better part of eight hours until it grew dark enougth for other Marines to chance a rescue to get out four of them from a killing zone. They jumped over the dike in what they called the Gates of Hell and get them all out. In the rescue attempt we lost another Marine but the Captain went back and brought back his body. He received the Silver Star for that action.<br><br>
Many held back their tears at the reunion I wish they hadn't. We took long sighs instead, bit our lips and shook each others hands tight. I hugged the Captain, My Captain and he melted in the embrace. He's only a little men but walked tall that day and we followed close behind. Gee it was great.  <br><br>
Ed;<br>
Thanks for being here and in Nam.
